The Python package `vokra` is a thin ctypes wrapper over the Vokra C ABI.
The prebuilt native library (`libvokra.dylib` / `libvokra.so` /
`vokra.dll`) shipped inside the wheel is produced from the Rust workspace
at the root of this repository; its licensing and third-party attributions
are recorded in the repository-root NOTICE file, which is authoritative
for all binary components of Vokra.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Build-time dependency: cbindgen (MPL-2.0, build-only)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Vokra C header (`include/vokra.h`) that this binding targets is
generated by cbindgen (Mozilla Public License 2.0). cbindgen is used
only at build time in the Rust workspace; no MPL-2.0 code is included in
the wheel artifact, and cbindgen is not a runtime dependency of this
Python package. See ADR-0003 for the build-only classification.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Build-time dependency: hatchling (MIT, build-only)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
This package uses hatchling as its PEP 517 build backend. hatchling is
declared in `[build-system].requires` in pyproject.toml and is not a
runtime dependency; it is not included in the wheel artifact.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Optional runtime interop: numpy (BSD-3-Clause, optional)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
numpy is an optional interop for zero-copy audio buffer exchange. It is
imported lazily inside `vokra.audio` and is never a hard install
dependency of the `vokra` package.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Zero third-party runtime dependencies
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Per Vokra invariant NFR-DS-02, `pip install vokra` MUST NOT pull any
Python package other than `vokra` itself. Any change to
`[project].dependencies` in pyproject.toml requires an update to this
NOTICE and a license audit (NFR-LC-02).
